<SUPPLEM>
<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=2 -->
SUPPLEMENTARY INFORMATION:
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Background 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
We are amending the Federal Seed Act Regulations in 7 CFR part 201 (referred to below as the regulations) by removing
the requirement that 10 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
percent of each container of alfalfa or red clover grown in Mexico be stained red. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
On December 8, 1993, President Clinton signed the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA), to become effective
January 1, 1994. To implement this agreement, Congress passed the North American Free Trade Agreement Implementation
Act (the Act) (Pub. L. 103&hyph;182). The statutory amendments included in the Act become effective coincident with
NAFTA. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The amendment in this final rule is mandated by section 361(a) of the Act, which amended section 302(e)(1) of the Federal
Seed Act (7 U.S.C. 1582(e)(1)) by providing that the provisions requiring certain seeds to be stained red shall not
apply to alfalfa or red clover seed originating in Mexico. (See Pub. L. 103&hyph;182). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
This final rule is being taken to conform the regulations with the amendments to the Act, by amending &sect;201.104
of the regulations to remove the origin staining requirements for seed of alfalfa and red clover grown in Mexico and
imported into the United States. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
Emergency Action 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The Administrator of the Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service has 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
determined that good cause exists to publish this final rule without prior 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
notice and opportunity for public comment. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Certain regulatory actions must be taken as a result of the statutory amendments discussed in the ``
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=4 -->
Background
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
,'' and must become effective with NAFTA to avoid inconsistency between the regulations and their statutory authority.
Removal of the origin staining requirement for alfalfa and red clover seed imported from Mexico is one of the regulatory
changes that must become effective at the same time as NAFTA and the Act to avoid this conflict. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
This action relieves a restriction on the importation of alfalfa and red clover seed from Mexico. Since prior notice
and other public procedures with respect to this final 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
rule are impracticable, unnecessary, and contrary to the public interest, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
since this regulatory change is mandated by Congress, there is good cause 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
under 5 U.S.C. 553 for making this final rule effective as of January 1, 1994. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
Executive Order 12866 and Regulatory Flexibility Act 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
This final rule has been reviewed under Executive Order 12866. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The Act, as amended, removes the requirement that alfalfa and red clover seed that is imported from Mexico be stained
red. This final rule conforms the regulations to the Act. We have no record of any alfalfa or red clover having been imported
from Mexico in the past 5 years, and we anticipate no importations in the foreseeable future. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Under these circumstances, the Administrator of the Animal and Plant 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Health Inspection Service has determined that this action will not have a 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
significant economic impact on a substantial number of small entities.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
Executive Order 12278
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
This rule has been reviewed under Executive Order 12778, Civil Justice 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Reform. This rule: (1) Preempts all State and local laws and regulations 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
that are inconsistent with this rule; (2) has no retroactive effect; and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) does not require administrative proceedings before parties may file suit 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
in court challenging this rule. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=84 g=1 f=1 -->
