<DOCNO> FR940106-0-00080 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940106-0-00021 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=2 -->
Congress enacted this legislation based on its finding of a shortage of RN's in the United States. See, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
e.g.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
, H.R. Rep. No. 101&hyph;288, 101st Cong., 1st Sess. 1&hyph;4 (October 16, 1989). Some health care facilities had
been relying on nonimmigrant RN's admitted under H&hyph;1 visas to meet this need. However, the numbers of visas available
for such aliens to adjust their immigration status to permanent residency had been limited. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Id
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
. at 2 and 3.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
At the time of INRA's enactment, many such RN's were approaching the end of their periods of admission to the United
States and faced return to their home countries. Many H&hyph;1 RN's potentially affected by the INRA were thought
to be employed in critical care and emergency service units. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Id
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
. at 2. The House Judiciary Committee found that departure of these H&hyph;1 RN's would have a detrimental impact on
the care provided to critically ill patients. 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
Id
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
. The INRA addressed this situation by permitting certain RN's who had H&hyph;1 status to become permanent residents.
Public Law 101&hyph;238, sec. 2, 8 U.S.C. 1255 note.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
At the same time, Congress was concerned about the perceived increased dependence of health care providers on foreign
RN's. As a result, the INA, as amended, links future access to nonimmigrant RN's to the taking of significant steps
by the facility to develop, recruit and retain U.S. workers in the registered nursing profession while ensuring that
the temporary foreign nurses admitted are protected in their employment and that their employment does not adversely
affect the employment of U.S. nurses. 8 U.S.C. 1182(m).
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Facilities are required to file attestations with DOL attesting to certain conditions and to steps taken to recruit
and retain U.S. nurses in order to reduce dependence on nonimmigrant alien nurses. Facilities are required to submit
these attestations to DOL as a condition to being able to petition INS for admission of H&hyph;1A nurses. The attestation
process is administered by ETA, while complaints and investigations regarding the attestations are handled by ESA.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The INRA-amended portions of the INA were amended by IMMACT to make clear that where nursing contractors are involved,
both the contractor and the worksite facility (other than private households) must file attestations, but granted
the Secretary of Labor (Secretary) some discretion in determining the requirements of the worksite facility attestation.
MTINA further amended the INA to clarify Congressional intent concerning the ``no lay off'' provision, to specify
that a facility that has laid off a nurse other than a staff nurse still meets the ``no lay off'' requirement, if it attests
that it will not replace the nurse with an H&hyph;1A nurse for 1 year after the lay off.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
B. Attestation Process
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The INA requires a health care facility seeking access to temporary foreign RN's (under the H&hyph;1A visa category)
to file an ``attestation'' with the Department of Labor (DOL or Department) on an annual basis. 8 U.S.C. 1101(a)(15)(H)(i)(a)
and 1182(m)(2)(A) and (C). This includes worksites (except private households) seeking to use the services of an
H&hyph;1A nurse through a nursing contractor. See IMMACT section 162(f). The attestation must assure that the following
six statutory criteria are met:
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) There would be a substantial disruption through no fault of the facility in the delivery of health care services
of the facility without the services of such alien(s). A facility is not considered to meet this clause if, within the
previous year, it laid off RN's, unless such RN's were other than staff nurses and the facility has attested that it
will not replace them with H&hyph;1A visa nurses. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) The employment of the alien(s) will not adversely affect the wages and working conditions of RN's similarly employed.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) The alien(s) employed by the facility will be paid the wage rate for RN's similarly employed by the facility.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) Either: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(a) The facility has taken and is taking timely and significant steps designed to recruit and retain sufficient RN's
who are United States citizens or immigrants who are authorized to perform nursing services, in order to remove as
quickly as reasonably possible the dependence of the facility on nonimmigrant RN's or 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(b) The facility is subject to an approved State plan for the recruitment and retention of nurses (see 8 U.S.C. 1182(m)(3)).
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(5) There is not a strike or lockout in the course of a labor dispute, and the employment of such alien(s) is not intended
or designed to influence an election for a bargaining representative for RN's of the facility.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(6) At the time of the filing of the petition for RN's, notice of the filing has been provided by the facility to the bargaining
representative of the RN's at the facility or, where there is none, notice of the filing has been provided to RN's employed
at the facility through posting in conspicuous locations.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
8 U.S.C. 1182(m)(2)(A)(i) through (vi).
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Each of the following is a ``significant step'' reasonably designed to recruit and retain RN's (see Item (4)(a) above):
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(i) Operating of training program for RN's at the facility or financing (or providing participation in) a training
program for RN's elsewhere;
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(ii) Providing career development programs and other methods of facilitating health care workers to become RN's;
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



<DOC>
<DOCNO> FR940106-0-00081 </DOCNO>
<PARENT> FR940106-0-00021 </PARENT>
<TEXT>
 
<!-- PJG STAG 4700 -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
(iii) Paying RN's wages at a rate higher than currently being paid to RN's similarly employed in the geographic area;

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(iv) Providing adequate support services to free RN's from administrative and other non-nursing duties; 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(v) Providing reasonable opportunities for meaningful salary advancement by RN's. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
8 U.S.C. 1182(m)(2)(B) (i) through (v); see 8 U.S.C. 1182(m)(2)(A)(iv)(I). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Items (i) through (v) above are not an exclusive list of the significant steps that may be taken to meet the requirements
of the fourth attestations element, and a facility is not required to take more than one step if the facility can demonstrate
than taking a second step is not reasonable. 8 U.S.C. 1182(m)(2)(B). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Special rules apply to cases where an alien nurse, for whom an employer has filed an attestation, is performing services
at a worksite other than the employer's worksite or other than a worksite controlled by the employer. In cases of temporary,
emergency circumstances, with respect to information not within the knowledge of the attestor, or for other good
cause, the Secretary may waive such requirements for the attestation for the worksite as the Secretary may determine
are appropriate, in order to avoid duplicative attestations. 8 U.S.C. 1182(m)(2)(A) (as amended by section 162(f)(2)(B)(iii)
of IMMACT). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
These attestations (and visa petitions supported by them) are available for public examination in the Employment
and Training Administration (ETA) National Office in Washington, D.C. 8 U.S.C. 1182(m)(2)(E)(i). The Department
also informs the Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS) which attestations have been accepted. The employer
must furnish evidence to INS that the Department has accepted its attestation for filing as a prerequisite for INS
approving a petition to bring in foreign RN's under H&hyph;1A visas (which visas are issued by the U.S. Department
of State (DOS)). 8 U.S.C. 1101(a)(15)(H)(i)(a). 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
In summary, DOL's administrative functions under the INRA include, with certain limited exceptions, receiving
and accepting attestations for filing, 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=3 -->
i.e., 
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
checking that the attestation form is properly completed and that the required explanatory statements are provided.
DOL reviews elements of attestations in only four instances: (1) the facility attests to a ``non-standards'' indicator
of substantial disruption (Element I); (2) the facility takes as one of its two steps a ``non-standard'' timely and
significant step (Element IV); (3) the facility attests that taking a second timely and significant step under Element
IV would not be reasonable; and (4) the facility is not an employer of H&hyph;1A nurses and is claiming a bona fide medical
emergency as the basis for requesting a waiver of one or more of the attestation elements. The Department also makes
the accepted attestations available for public inspection, and notifies INS of those attestations that DOL has on
file. These administration functions are delegated, by regulation, to ETA. 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
C. Complaints, Investigations and Enforcement
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
The Department is also authorized to investigate allegations that a facility has failed to meet the conditions attested
to or that a facility has misrepresented a material fact in an attestation. 8 U.S.C. 1182(m)(2)(E) (ii) through (v).
If violations are found, DOL may impose administrative remedies, including civil money penalties (CMP's); shall
notify the Attorney General, who shall not approve H&hyph;1A petitions for a period of at least 1 year for the facility;
shall obtain back wages; and may impose other remedies. These activities constitute the Department's enforcement
functions under the INRA. Under the regulations, the enforcement functions are delegated to the Department's Employment
Standards Administration (ESA), Wage and Hour Division.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=83 g=1 f=1 -->
D. Advisory Group
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG ITAG l=11 g=1 f=1 -->
Finally, pursuant to the INRA, the Secretary appointed an advisory group which includes representatives of DOL,
the Department of Health and Human Services, the Attorney General, hospitals, and labor organizations representing
RN's. Pub. L. 101&hyph;238 section 3(c)(2), 103 Stat. at 2103.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
Under the INRA, the advisory group advises the Secretary on: 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(1) The impact of this legislation on the nursing shortage, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(2) Programs that health care facilities may implement to recruit and retain U.S. RN's, 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(3) State recruitment and retention plans, and 
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
(4) The advisability of extending the law beyond the current 5-year duration of this pilot program.
<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->

<!-- PJG 0012 frnewline -->
The advisory group operates under the auspices of the DOL Office of the Assistant Secretary for Policy.
<!-- PJG /ITAG -->

<!-- PJG /STAG -->
</TEXT>
</DOC>



